# Native gfx1013 rocBLAS SGEMM sweep — PATCHED amdgpu module (flush_pasid_uses_kiq = false).
# Board: Fedora 43, kernel 6.18.9-200.fc43, ROCm 6.4.2. No HSA_OVERRIDE.
#
# Why 24 CU: in the kernel tree used here the BC-250 40-CU unlock write lives inside
# gfx_v10_0_kiq_reset_hw_queue(), i.e. it only fires when a KIQ hardware queue is reset. The
# correctness patch removes the KIQ activity that (on the stock driver) incidentally triggers
# that reset, so the unlock never fires and the board comes up at 24 CU. We verified the loaded
# module was the patched one (its decompressed binary matched the freshly built .ko and differed
# from stock) and that dmesg reported "active_cu_number 24".

# --- single-size sweep: every size wedges ---
N=256   -> timeout / wedge   (dmesg: "cp queue preemption time out")
N=512   -> timeout / wedge   (dmesg: "cp queue preemption time out")
N=1024  -> timeout / wedge   (dmesg: "cp queue preemption time out")
N=2048  -> timeout / wedge   (dmesg: "cp queue preemption time out")

# dmesg during the sweep:
#   amdgpu: cp queue preemption time out.
#   amdgpu: cp queue preemption time out.
#   amdgpu: cp queue preemption time out.
#   amdgpu: Resetting wave fronts (nocpsch) on dev 00000000a3f1a4ab

# Reading of this (offered tentatively): at 24 CU even a tiny GEMM wedges, so the correctness
# patch and a working 40-CU compute queue could not be had at the same time on this board — the
# unlock is entangled with the very KIQ reset the patch removes. A soft reboot after these wedges
# did not recover the queue; a hard power-cycle was needed. Back on the stock module at 40 CU the
# same GEMMs (N=512, N=2048) were correct again.
